I think you’re pointing at something interesting.

If we write a delta simply as

\Delta X

then yes, every delta represents a transformation from one state to another:

X_t \rightarrow X_{t+\Delta t}

The delta is the difference between those states.

Now consider what changes.

If the independent variable is time, then

\frac{\Delta X}{\Delta t}

is the rate of transformation (velocity, growth rate, information rate, etc.).

But time isn’t the only coordinate you can move along.

You can have:

* \Delta x — movement through space
* \Delta E — change in energy
* \Delta I — change in information
* \Delta M — change in memory
* \Delta A — change in attention
* \Delta T — change in trust
* \Delta P — change in probability
* \Delta S — change in semantic state

In that view, time is just one axis over which transformations can be parameterized.

Even more abstractly:

A delta is evidence that a transformation has occurred.

Then calculus becomes “the mathematics of infinitesimal transformations.”

⸻

Your second thought—“this change is time or reversed”—is also worth unpacking.

If you know the transformation F,

X_{t+1} = F(X_t),

then running it “forward” generates the future.

If F has an inverse,

X_t = F^{-1}(X_{t+1}),

you can reconstruct a past state. In mathematics that’s just applying the inverse transformation. In physics, whether this is actually possible depends on the system: some idealized laws are approximately time-reversible, while many real-world processes (like mixing cream into coffee or biological aging) are effectively irreversible because of increasing entropy and information loss.

That suggests a compact principle:

Time can be viewed as the ordering of transformations, while a delta measures the transformation between ordered states.

You could even write a very general state-update equation:

\text{State}_{n+1}
=
\text{Transform}(\text{State}_n),

where the index n need not be physical time. It could be any ordered progression—iterations of an algorithm, stages of learning, steps in a proof, or updates to a belief state.

This perspective is useful because it unifies many domains without assuming they’re identical: what changes from field to field is what the state is and what transformation rules govern it, not the abstract idea of moving from one state to another.